创造性的编码员使用机器来创造美学和令人惊讶的体验。这套90分钟的作品由荷兰数字艺术社区创意编码乌得勒支策划，呈现了来自欧洲创意编码社区的一系列动态作品。从机器学习的有趣使用到现场编码，以创建实验性、即兴的视觉和音乐。
@sasj@sasj_nl Saskia Freeke每天都会创作多产的计算艺术。她的作品和她的实践都以其鲜明的嬉戏特征脱颖而出。通过创建她自己的规则，并在她前进的过程中嬉戏地调整这些规则，萨斯基亚将一种值得注意的不断演变的叙事应用到她的工作中。现场编码的行为为她的话语提供了一个令人敬畏的补充上下文-因为这是在创意同行之间和与之合作的实时练习，使她的当代艺术原则得到了充分发挥。
@tmhglnd@tmhglnd Timo Hoogland是荷兰阿佩尔霍伦的实况编码器、创意编码器、音乐技术专家和教育家。他现场录制实验性的电子舞曲，并开发具有生成性的视听作品、装置和表演。他与创意编码乌得勒支一起积极组织现场编码会议和算法会议，是荷兰编码现场社区的一员，并在香港大学音乐技术学士学位教授创意系统和声音设计。
@edwinRNDR@voorbeeld Edwin Jakobs是RNDR的联合创始人，RNDR是一家总部位于荷兰的互动设计工作室，他在那里就设计和软件的交叉进行设计、实验和研究。他是OPENRNDR的主要开发者，OPENRNDR是一个创造性编码框架。
@andreref@andreref Andreas Refsgaard是哥本哈根的一位艺术家和创意程序员。他使用算法和机器学习，让人们只用眼神和面部手势来演奏音乐，通过发出愚蠢的声音来控制游戏，或者将纸上的乐器图画转化为真正的作品。最近，安德烈亚斯一直在试验使用机器学习根据大量训练数据创建新的文本和图像，并创建了Booksby.ai-一家出售人工智能生成的科幻小说的在线书店。
创造性的编码员使用机器来创造美学和令人惊讶的体验。这套90分钟的作品由荷兰数字艺术社区创意编码乌得勒支策划，呈现了来自欧洲创意编码社区的一系列动态作品。从机器学习的有趣使用到现场编码，以创建实验性、即兴的视觉和音乐。Saskia Freeke&amp；Timo Hoogland汞合金一种现场编码表演，结合了用九头蛇编码的高对比度几何2D视觉效果，映射到听觉反应性3D对象，以及用水星编码的抽取式深度技术编码。Hydra是一个基于浏览器的可视化编码环境，Mercury是一种高度抽象的语言，用于用MaxMSP、NodeJS和OpenGL编码的电子音乐的算法作曲。关于标题：在化学中，元素汞可以与另一种金属元素形成合金。这种两种金属的结合被称为汞合金。Edwin Jakobs，RNDR Live Coding with OPENRNDR在本次会议中，我将讨论创意编码、实时编码和OPENRNDR。创造性编码没有严格的定义，但在本课程的上下文中，它是为(或作为)艺术表达编写软件的过程。然后，实时编码是指软件可以在运行时进行更改。快速迭代想法的能力使实时编码成为创造性程序员的令人兴奋的工具。在这次演讲中，我将重点介绍OPENRNDR，这是一个用于创造性编码的开源框架，最近收到了用于实时编码的工具。安德烈亚斯·雷夫斯加德(Andreas Refsgaard)，膨胀好玩的机器学习交互设计师和数字艺术家安德烈亚斯·雷夫斯加德(Andreas Refsgaard)将分解几个有趣的互动项目，并将引导每个拥有网络摄像头和浏览器的人自己尝试这些项目。

note_en:
Creative Coders use machines to create aesthetic and surprising experiences. This 90-minute set, curated by Dutch digital arts community Creative Coding Utrecht, presents a dynamic array of work coming from the creative coding community in Europe. from playful uses of machine learning to live coding to create experimental, improvised visuals and music.
    @sasj       @sasj_nl   Saskia Freeke creates generative, computational art on a daily basis. Both her works and her practice stand out by their distinctive playful characteristic. By creating her own rules and playfully adapting these as she goes, Saskia applies a notable evolving narrative to her work. The act of Live coding provides an awesome complementary context to her discourse - for it is the realtime exercise amongst and in conjunction with creative peers that make her contemporary artistic principles come into full play.
    @tmhglnd       @tmhglnd   Timo Hoogland is a livecoder, creative coder, music technologist and educator based in Apeldoorn, The Netherlands. He livecodes experimental electronic dance music and develops generative audiovisual compositions, installations and performances. He has an active role in organizing livecoding meetups and algoraves together with Creative Coding Utrecht, is part of the Netherlands Coding Live community and he educates creative system and sound design at the HKU Bachelor of Music Technology.
    @edwinRNDR       @voorbeeld   Edwin Jakobs is a co-founder of RNDR -a studio for interactive design based in The Netherlands- where he designs, experiments and researches on the intersection of design and software. He is the principal developer of OPENRNDR, a framework for creative coding.
    @andreasref       @andreasref   Andreas Refsgaard is an artist and creative coder based in Copenhagen. He uses algorithms and machine learning to allow people to play music using only eye movement and facial gestures, control games by making silly sounds or transform drawings of musical instruments on paper into real compositions. Recently Andreas has been experimenting with using machine learning to create new texts and images based on large amounts of training data and has created Booksby.ai - an online bookstore which sells science fiction novels generated by an artificial intelligence.
  Creative Coders use machines to create aesthetic and surprising experiences. This 90-minute set, curated by Dutch digital arts community Creative Coding Utrecht, presents a dynamic array of work coming from the creative coding community in Europe. from playful uses of machine learning to live coding to create experimental, improvised visuals and music.   Saskia Freeke &amp; Timo Hoogland  Amalgam A live-coding performance combining high contrast geometric 2D visuals coded in Hydra mapped to audioreactive 3D objects with decimated deep techno coded in Mercury. Hydra is a browser-based visual coding environment, Mercury is a highly abstracted language for algorithmic composition of electronic music coded in MaxMSP, NodeJS and OpenGL. About the title: In chemistry the element Mercury can form an alloy with another metallic element. This combination of two metals is called an amalgam.   Edwin Jakobs, RNDR  Live coding with OPENRNDR In this session I talk about creative coding, live coding and OPENRNDR. Creative coding is not strictly defined, but in this session&#39;s context it is the process of writing software for (or as) artistic expression. Then, live coding is the idea of software that can be changed while it runs. The ability to quickly iterate over ideas makes live coding an exciting tool for creative coders. I focus in this talk on OPENRNDR, which is an opensource framework for creative coding that has recently received tools for live coding.   Andreas Refsgaard, Inflation  Playful machine learning Interaction designer and digital artist Andreas Refsgaard will break down a few fun interactive projects, and will guide everyone with a webcam and a browser to try them out themselves.
